## What this project enforces

- scope and intent are managed through a dedicated scope agent
- scope conversations are retained in SQLite-backed memory at `{{ scope_memory_path }}`
- all code changes must pass local quality gates before QA review starts
- QA review is config-driven and can fan out across specialized reviewer personas
- every reviewer finding is triaged against scope and all in-scope findings must be fixed
- small changes review the changed surface; milestone changes trigger full-repo review
- branch coverage must stay at or above `{{ coverage_threshold }}`

## Quickstart

If you generated this project with `copier copy --trust ...`, the post-copy bootstrap should already have:
- installed Python `{{ python_version }}` with `uv`
- created `.venv`
- installed the dev dependencies, including `uv` inside the environment
- initialized the scope and review-state databases
- installed the pre-commit hooks if this project already had a `.git` directory

To verify the fresh project, run:

```bash
uv run python tools/run_full_test_suite.py
uv run python tools/run_pre_commit.py
```

If you cloned the generated project from git on another machine, rerun bootstrap before development:

```bash
uv python install {{ python_version }}
uv run --python {{ python_version }} python tools/install_dev_dependencies.py --bootstrap --python-version {{ python_version }}
uv run python tools/init_scope_memory.py
uv run python tools/init_review_state.py
uv run python tools/install_pre_commit.py
```

If you ever need to rerun bootstrap manually:

```bash
uv python install {{ python_version }}
uv run --python {{ python_version }} python tools/install_dev_dependencies.py --bootstrap --python-version {{ python_version }}
uv run python tools/init_scope_memory.py
uv run python tools/init_review_state.py
uv run python tools/install_pre_commit.py
```

## Control Plane

The repository keeps Claude-facing workflow material in `.claude/` so the agent can read project rules without ingesting unrelated source files by default.

The workflow files are intentionally structured so they can be mapped into LangGraph nodes, edges, and state later without needing to rework the repo layout.

This project was rendered with `{{ model_provider }}` as the default runtime provider, so `.claude/config/runtime.yaml` points first at {% if model_provider == "anthropic" %}Anthropic Claude{% else %}Google Gemini{% endif %} credentials and model aliases while still preserving Claude/Codex/Gemini compatibility entrypoints.

Codex/OpenAI compatibility in this template is control-plane and `CODEX_*` model-alias support, not a third generated runtime provider.

The provider-facing entrypoints `CLAUDE.md`, `GEMINI.md`, `AGENTS.md`, and `.codex/manifest.md` intentionally share the same read order, workflow loop, and non-negotiable rules so provider changes do not change the project contract.

- `CLAUDE.md`: canonical entry point for Claude-first tooling
- `GEMINI.md`: compatibility entry point for Gemini CLI context discovery
- `AGENTS.md`: compatibility entry point for AGENTS-based tooling
- `.claude/manifest.md`: canonical control-plane index
- `.codex/manifest.md`: compatibility handoff for Codex-style discovery
- `.claude/config/runtime.yaml`: runtime defaults and quality thresholds
- `.claude/config/project-surfaces.yaml`: explicit flags for model, prompt, and data-contract surfaces
- `.claude/config/quality-gates.yaml`: authoritative local QA commands and blocked-state handling
- `.claude/config/review-scope.yaml`: authoritative delta/full review rules and triggers
- `.claude/config/trigger-derivation.yaml`: deterministic mapping from change metadata to normalized review triggers
- `.claude/config/finding-contract.yaml`: canonical reviewer finding payload and example
- `.claude/config/workflow.yaml`: review/fix loop definition
- `.claude/config/reviewers.yaml`: registry of enabled reviewers
- `.claude/config/lightning.yaml`: optional Agent Lightning optimization settings and boundaries
- `.claude/config/telemetry.yaml`: optional passive telemetry capture for optimization
- `.claude/agents/`: agent specifications and reviewer perspectives
- `.claude/policies/`: quality, finding-quality, optimization-boundary, and review-scope rules
- `.claude/memory/`: SQLite scope-memory schema and conventions
- `contracts/`: optional project-specific schemas and data-contract artifacts
- `tools/init_scope_memory.py`: idempotent local SQLite bootstrap for scope memory
- `tools/init_review_state.py`: idempotent local SQLite bootstrap for review runs and findings
- `tools/verify_scope_memory.py`: non-mutating check for local scope-memory readiness
- `tools/verify_review_state.py`: non-mutating check for local review-state readiness
- `tools/install_dev_dependencies.py`: install or refresh dev dependencies, preferring `uv.lock` when present
- `tools/install_pre_commit.py`: install pre-commit hooks only when this project is a git repo
- `tools/run_pre_commit.py`: run pre-commit only when this project is a git repo
- `tools/run_eval_gate.py`: scaffold-aware eval gate wrapper
- `tools/run_data_contract_gate.py`: scaffold-aware data-contract gate wrapper
- `tools/run_full_test_suite.py`: run the regular test suite without re-running eval or data-contract marker suites
- `tools/init_lightning_telemetry.py`: optional SQLite bootstrap for optimization telemetry
- `tools/record_lightning_trace.py`: optional telemetry ingestion hook for workflow traces
- `tools/export_lightning_dataset.py`: optional JSONL exporter for Agent Lightning datasets

## Working Agreement

1. Confirm or refine scope before implementation begins.
2. Keep implementation inside the approved scope.
3. Run `uv lock` during bootstrap and commit `uv.lock` when dependencies change.
4. Run local quality gates before QA review.
5. Gather reviewer findings from all enabled reviewers.
6. Let scope triage decide which findings are in-scope.
7. Fix every in-scope finding and rerun the quality gates.
8. Repeat until no in-scope findings remain.

## Review Modes

- `delta`: default for small, localized changes
- `full`: required for milestone work, broad refactors, dependency changes, schema changes, or any other cross-cutting update described in `.claude/policies/review-scope.md`

## Reviewer Findings

Reviewers are expected to produce structured findings with exact file evidence, severity, confidence, expected versus observed behavior, and a scope anchor when they claim an issue is in-scope. The canonical payload lives in `.claude/config/finding-contract.yaml`, and the severity/evidence rubric lives in `.claude/policies/finding-quality.md`.

The generated project includes real starter-level `eval` and `data_contract` gates by default. They validate control-plane integrity and contract scaffolding now, and you should replace or extend them with real prompt, model, schema, and compatibility checks as the project evolves. See `.claude/policies/release-readiness.md` for the point at which starter checks stop being sufficient.

If you use Gemini CLI, keep `GEMINI.md` at the repo root so Gemini can discover the canonical `.claude/` control plane automatically.

Use `tests/evals/` for project-specific eval cases and `tests/data_contracts/` for project-specific contract checks when those surfaces become real.

## Optional Agent Lightning

The template includes optional Agent Lightning scaffolding for development-workflow optimization only.

- it may optimize execution strategy, reviewer quality, review-mode recommendation, and remediation efficiency
- it may try to reduce total LLM queries and estimated LLM cost to reach a full QA pass
- it must not define scope, triage scope, or change hard governance rules
- it is future-ready scaffolding; real runtime instrumentation should call `tools/record_lightning_trace.py` or an equivalent adapter

If you want to enable the optional optimization layer later:

```bash
uv sync --dev --group lightning
uv run python tools/init_lightning_telemetry.py
uv run python tools/record_lightning_trace.py sample_trace.json
uv run python tools/export_lightning_dataset.py
uv run python tools/purge_lightning_telemetry.py
```

The optimization layer is disabled by default and remains subordinate to `.claude/policies/lightning-boundaries.md`.

## Adding A Reviewer

1. Add a new reviewer specification under `.claude/agents/`
2. Register it in `.claude/config/reviewers.yaml`
3. Add or update tests that validate the registry and expected behavior
4. Document any new full-review triggers if the reviewer is only relevant for certain change classes

